---
import BaseLayout from '../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Editorial Intelligence"
  description="Editorial Intelligence is the practice of identifying, connecting and developing organisational knowledge into strategic narratives and reusable assets."
>
  <article class="container-site py-20">
    <div class="max-w-2xl">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="mb-16">
        <p class="t-label mb-6">The discipline</p>
        <h1 class="t-display mb-6">Editorial Intelligence</h1>
        <p class="t-body text-lg leading-relaxed">
          A manifesto for an emerging discipline.
        </p>
        <p class="t-small mt-4 italic">
          Version 1. This framework evolves as new evidence is added.
        </p>
        <a href="/start" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.375rem;margin-top:1.25rem;font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--color-ink-tertiary);text-decoration:none;" class="hover:text-[var(--color-ink)] transition-colors">
          New to Editorial Intelligence? Start here →
        </a>
      </header>

      <!-- Hierarchy -->
      <div class="hierarchy mb-16">
        {[
          { num: '01', label: 'Editorial Intelligence', sub: 'The discipline', href: '/intelligence', current: true },
          { num: '02', label: 'Evidence Engine', sub: 'The infrastructure — captures and connects signals', href: '/frameworks/evidence-engine' },
          { num: '03', label: 'EI Cycle', sub: 'The operating model — turns evidence into action and learning', href: '#cycle' },
          { num: '04', label: 'Daily OS', sub: 'The daily practice', href: '/frameworks/daily-os' },
          { num: '05', label: 'Applications', sub: 'Proof in the real world', href: '/narratives' },
        ].map((level, i) => (
          <div class="hierarchy-row">
            {i > 0 && <div class="hierarchy-connector" aria-hidden="true">↓</div>}
            <a href={level.href} class:list={['hierarchy-item', level.current && 'hierarchy-item--current']}>
              <span class="hierarchy-num">{level.num}</span>
              <span class="hierarchy-label">{level.label}</span>
              <span class="hierarchy-sub">{level.sub}</span>
            </a>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 1. The problem -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">The problem</h2>
        <div class="prose-section">
          <p>Every organisation is trying to make sense of change.</p>
          <p>They invest in research, listen to customers, run webinars, attend industry events, build products and accumulate expertise. Every day they generate valuable signals about the markets they serve, the problems their customers face and the direction their industry is heading.</p>
          <p>Yet these signals rarely become a coherent point of view.</p>
          <p>Research is published once and forgotten. Customer stories remain isolated. Product knowledge stays within teams. Webinar and event insights disappear into recordings and presentation decks. AI produces more content, but without a distinctive perspective to guide it.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">The challenge is not a lack of information.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">It is the inability to connect that information into something larger than the sum of its parts.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 2. The discipline -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">The discipline</h2>
        <div class="prose-section">
          <p>Editorial Intelligence is the practice of identifying, connecting and developing organisational knowledge into strategic narratives and reusable assets.</p>
          <p>It begins with signals — the research findings, customer experiences, product insights, market observations and operational evidence that organisations generate continuously but rarely connect.</p>
          <p>It synthesises those signals into insights: meaningful patterns that reveal something true about customers, markets or the direction of an industry.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">Editorial judgement determines which patterns are strategically meaningful and which are simply noise.</p>
          <p>It organises those insights into narratives: strategic stories that give an organisation a coherent point of view, developed over time rather than produced once and forgotten.</p>
          <p>And it activates those narratives through formats and channels suited to each audience and purpose — articles, frameworks, case studies, video, social content, sales enablement, event presentations — designed from the start to be discovered, reused and extended.</p>
          <p>But the process does not end with publication.</p>
          <p>Every asset creates new signals. Every new signal strengthens the narrative. Editorial Intelligence is designed as a continuous learning system rather than a linear production process.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">The result is not a content programme. It is a knowledge system that learns.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 3. The cycle -->
      <section id="cycle" class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">The Editorial Intelligence Cycle</h2>
        <div class="distinction-callout mb-10">
          <div class="distinction-item">
            <a href="/frameworks/evidence-engine" class="distinction-link">
              <span class="distinction-label">Evidence Engine</span>
              <span class="distinction-role">Infrastructure</span>
              <span class="distinction-desc">Where signals are captured, connected and organised. The reporters, archives and databases. The engine under the bonnet.</span>
            </a>
          </div>
          <div class="distinction-sep" aria-hidden="true">powers</div>
          <div class="distinction-item">
            <span class="distinction-label">EI Cycle</span>
            <span class="distinction-role">Operating model</span>
            <span class="distinction-desc">How that evidence becomes narrative, action and learning. The deciding, writing, publishing and following up. The driving.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="prose-section">
          <p>Editorial Intelligence is not a linear process. It is a cycle.</p>
          <p>Every organisation that practises it moves through the same sequence — not once, but continuously, with each pass strengthening the work that came before.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Cycle steps -->
        <div class="cycle-steps mt-10">
          {[
            {
              term: 'Signals',
              def: 'Signals are observations that have the potential to change or strengthen an organisation\'s strategic understanding — customer interviews, research findings, product feedback, sales conversations, event discussions, market observations. Most organisations generate signals continuously. Few have a system for recognising which ones matter. Editorial judgement begins here, with the discipline of distinguishing meaningful observations from background noise.',
            },
            {
              term: 'Synthesis',
              def: 'Signals become insights through synthesis — the recognition that multiple observations from different sources are pointing at the same underlying truth. Not every signal survives synthesis. Most don\'t. The editorial judgement required here is the capacity to sit with incomplete evidence long enough to recognise what it is actually revealing, and to resist the impulse to publish before the pattern is clear.',
            },
            {
              term: 'Narratives',
              def: 'Narratives are where organisational knowledge becomes strategic direction. They provide the organising structure that connects evidence across time, teams and channels — becoming more authoritative as new evidence is added, and more distinctive as they develop over time. Narratives are the centre of the Editorial Intelligence Cycle. Everything before them exists to discover them. Everything after them exists to strengthen them.',
            },
            {
              term: 'Activation',
              def: 'Narratives are activated through the formats and channels suited to the audience and purpose — articles, frameworks, diagnostics, case studies, AI workflows, playbooks, video, social content, event presentations, sales enablement, executive communications. Format and channel selection is a strategic decision, not an afterthought. The question at this stage is not "how do we produce content?" but "which form will make this narrative most useful to this audience, in this context?"',
            },
            {
              term: 'Evidence',
              def: 'Every piece of activated content generates new evidence. A published article surfaces new questions. A social post reveals what resonates. A webinar generates new practitioner insights. A diagnostic uncovers new patterns. A framework, tested in practice, either holds or requires refinement. That evidence feeds back into the cycle as new signals — refining the narrative, strengthening the position, making the next pass more valuable than the previous one.',
            },
            {
              term: 'Learning and reuse',
              def: 'The final stage closes the loop. Evidence is applied: the narrative is refined where it needs sharpening, high-performing elements are repurposed in new contexts, and the signal capture capability that feeds into the next cycle improves with each pass. The organisation does not simply produce better content over time. It becomes more intelligent — a system that compounds its editorial knowledge rather than starting fresh with each campaign.',
            },
          ].map((step, i) => (
            <div class="cycle-step">
              <div class="cycle-step__marker">
                <span class="t-label">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}</span>
                {i < 5 && <div class="cycle-step__line" aria-hidden="true" />}
              </div>
              <div class="cycle-step__content">
                <h3 class="t-title mb-3">{step.term}</h3>
                <p class="t-body">{step.def}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <div class="mt-10 prose-section">
          <p>This is the Editorial Intelligence Cycle.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">Not a workflow that ends with publication. A system that learns.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 4. In practice -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Editorial Intelligence in practice</h2>
        <div class="prose-section mb-10">
          <p>The principles of Editorial Intelligence did not emerge from theory.</p>
          <p>They emerged from work.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="flex flex-col gap-8">
          {[
            {
              title: 'Hidden Hours',
              href: '/narratives/hidden-hours',
              body: 'Hidden Hours began as a research project into the invisible pressures facing accounting professionals — compliance burden, workflow friction, late payments, business change. The research uncovered a pattern: the operational challenges accountants described were not isolated problems. They were expressions of a deeper structural pressure on the profession. That pattern became a narrative. The narrative attracted more evidence — customer stories, practitioner interviews, event conversations, product feedback, regulatory changes. Each new signal strengthened the position. The narrative became a framework. The framework became a diagnostic. The diagnostic became an AI workflow. Hidden Hours is not a content campaign. It is a knowledge system that has compounded over time.',
            },
            {
              title: 'Customer Stories',
              href: '/narratives/customer-stories',
              body: 'Most organisations treat customer stories as marketing assets — produced once, used briefly, then filed. At Sage, customer stories became something different: a continuously developing body of evidence about how real organisations solve operational problems. Rather than isolated case studies, they became connected evidence — each story adding to a growing picture of how businesses experience change, adopt technology and navigate pressure. The stories didn\'t just demonstrate product value. They became a strategic intelligence resource.',
            },
            {
              title: 'Trusted AI',
              href: '/narratives/trusted-ai',
              body: 'When AI became a dominant industry conversation, the instinctive response for many organisations was to produce content about AI — announcements, explainers, opinion pieces. Trusted AI took a different approach. It began with a question: what do organisations actually need to know to implement AI responsibly? The answer required connecting research, governance thinking, customer experience and practical implementation evidence. The result was a coherent point of view on how trust in AI is built — developed through evidence, expressed through multiple assets, designed to strengthen over time.',
            },
          ].map((example) => (
            <div class="practice-example">
              <h3 class="t-title mb-3">
                <a href={example.href} class="text-[var(--color-ink)] no-underline hover:text-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors">
                  {example.title}
                </a>
              </h3>
              <p class="t-body">{example.body}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <div class="mt-10 prose-section">
          <p>Three examples. Three different starting points — research, customer evidence, emerging technology. Three different outputs. The same underlying process.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">Signals recognised. Synthesised into insights. Narratives built. Activated across formats and channels. Evidence accumulated. Learning applied.</p>
          <p>That is Editorial Intelligence in practice.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 5. Principles -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-4">The four principles of Editorial Intelligence</h2>
        <p class="t-small mb-10">These principles emerged through practice and have been refined through repeated application. They are not rules. They are the beliefs that have proven most useful in developing organisational knowledge into strategic assets.</p>

        <div class="flex flex-col gap-10">
          {[
            {
              title: 'Knowledge before content',
              body: 'Content is not the starting point. The starting point is organisational knowledge — research, customer insight, product expertise, market signals, operational experience. Content is one way that knowledge is expressed. It is never the source of it. Organisations that begin with content ask: what should we publish? Organisations that practise Editorial Intelligence ask: what do we know, and what does it mean?',
            },
            {
              title: 'Narratives over campaigns',
              body: 'Campaigns have a beginning and an end. Narratives evolve. A strong narrative connects multiple signals across months or years, accumulating evidence and authority with each new piece of work. It does not reset with each campaign cycle. It compounds. The measure of a narrative is not how many assets it produces. It is how much stronger the position becomes over time.',
            },
            {
              title: 'Evidence over assertion',
              body: 'Strategic positions are earned through accumulated evidence rather than asserted through isolated ideas. Research findings, customer experience, operational examples and market observations — each new piece either strengthens the position or refines it. The narrative becomes more authoritative not because it is stated with more confidence, but because it is supported by more evidence. Thought leadership communicates a point of view. Editorial Intelligence develops and strengthens one over time.',
            },
            {
              title: 'Editorial judgement before AI scale',
              body: 'AI accelerates production. It summarises, drafts, translates and distributes at a speed no editorial team can match. But acceleration without direction produces volume, not value. Editorial judgement determines which signals matter, which insights are worth developing, which narratives deserve investment and which assets will remain useful over time. It is the capacity to distinguish between what is merely interesting and what is strategically meaningful. In an AI-enabled workflow, editorial judgement does not diminish in importance. It becomes the scarcest and most valuable resource in the system.',
            },
          ].map((principle, i) => (
            <div class="principle">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <span class="t-label mt-1 shrink-0 w-6">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}</span>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="t-title mb-3">{principle.title}</h3>
                  <p class="t-body">{principle.body}</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 5b. The operating model -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">The operating model</h2>
        <div class="prose-section mb-10">
          <p>At a higher level of abstraction, the cycle that powers Editorial Intelligence can be described in five stages.</p>
          <p>This is not a new cycle. It is the same cycle described at the level of the whole organisation — showing where every team, channel and communication discipline connects to the same intelligence foundation.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Five-stage loop diagram -->
        <div class="loop-diagram">
          {[
            {
              stage: 'Signals',
              desc: 'Customer research, interviews, webinars and events, sales conversations, market trends, operational data',
              color: 'var(--color-ink-secondary)',
            },
            {
              stage: 'Editorial Intelligence',
              desc: 'Identify recurring problems, connect evidence, develop narratives, prioritise opportunities',
              color: 'var(--color-accent)',
            },
            {
              stage: 'Narrative Development',
              desc: 'Build reusable frameworks, strategic stories and editorial assets that compound over time',
              color: 'var(--color-ink-secondary)',
            },
            {
              stage: 'Activation',
              desc: 'PR, editorial, thought leadership, customer marketing, sales enablement, social, events, executive communications',
              color: 'var(--color-blue, #6a9fd8)',
            },
            {
              stage: 'Learning',
              desc: 'Coverage, engagement, customer feedback, sales conversations, new market signals — fed back into the system',
              color: 'var(--color-ink-secondary)',
            },
          ].map((item, i) => (
            <div class="loop-stage">
              <div class="loop-stage__connector">
                <span class="loop-stage__num">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}</span>
                {i < 4 && <div class="loop-stage__line" />}
                {i === 4 && <div class="loop-stage__return">↺</div>}
              </div>
              <div class="loop-stage__content">
                <h3 class="loop-stage__name" style={`color: ${item.color}`}>{item.stage}</h3>
                <p class="loop-stage__desc">{item.desc}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <div class="prose-section mt-10">
          <p>This is the complete operating model. Each stage feeds the next. Learning feeds back into signals. The cycle never ends — it compounds.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="/activation" class="activation-cta">
          How Editorial Intelligence powers every communication channel
          <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </a>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 6. The OS -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">Editorial Intelligence OS</h2>
        <div class="prose-section mb-10">
          <p>Philosophy without implementation remains theoretical.</p>
          <p>The Editorial Intelligence Cycle describes how knowledge becomes strategic assets. The Editorial Intelligence OS is the infrastructure that makes that cycle repeatable.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          {[
            { name: 'Research Library', desc: 'Signal and insight repositories that feed the cycle continuously.', href: '/frameworks/evidence-engine' },
            { name: 'Narrative Library', desc: 'Connected narratives, frameworks and editorial assets for discovery and reuse.', href: '/narratives' },
            { name: 'Workflow Library', desc: 'Repeatable editorial processes that improve with each iteration.', href: '/frameworks/workflow-library' },
            { name: 'AI Agents', desc: 'AI-enabled workflows that accelerate production from connected knowledge.', href: '/ai-systems' },
            { name: 'Editorial Activation', desc: 'Where intelligence becomes communication. Every channel draws from the same narrative foundation.', href: '/frameworks/editorial-activation', highlight: true },
            { name: 'Daily OS', desc: 'The operational rhythm that keeps the cycle running — signal capture, narrative review, activation planning, feedback collection.', href: '/frameworks/daily-os' },
          ].map((component) => (
            <a href={component.href} class:list={['os-component', component.highlight && 'os-component--highlight']}>
              <p class="t-small font-medium mb-1" style={component.highlight ? 'color: var(--color-accent)' : 'color: var(--color-ink)'}>{component.name}</p>
              <p class="t-small">{component.desc}</p>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>

        <p class="t-small mt-8 italic">
          The Editorial Intelligence OS is documented here as a working implementation. It will evolve as the discipline develops.
        </p>

        <div class="os-links mt-8">
          <a href="/dashboard" class="os-link-item">Dashboard OS — the operating system in detail →</a>
          <a href="/practice" class="os-link-item">In practice — worked examples and evidence →</a>
          <a href="/experiments" class="os-link-item">Experiments — active workflows and tools →</a>
          <a href="/cycle" class="os-link-item">The cycle — the full model →</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider mb-16" />

      <!-- 7. The ambition -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="t-label mb-8">The ambition</h2>
        <div class="prose-section">
          <p>Editorial Intelligence began as a way of describing a particular kind of work.</p>
          <p>It has become something larger.</p>
          <p>The organisations that will build lasting strategic advantage in the AI era will not be those that produce the most content. They will be those that best understand what they know, connect it into coherent positions and build systems that make that knowledge more valuable over time.</p>
          <p>AI changes the economics of content production entirely. It does not change the value of genuine organisational knowledge, coherent strategic narratives or the editorial judgement required to develop them. If anything, as content becomes abundant, those things become scarcer and more valuable.</p>
          <p>Editorial Intelligence is the discipline of building that value deliberately.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">Not by publishing more.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">By knowing more.</p>
          <p>And by building systems that ensure that knowledge compounds — across teams, across time, across every new cycle of evidence.</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-[var(--color-ink)]">The organisation that practises Editorial Intelligence does not simply produce better content. It becomes more intelligent over time.</p>
          <p style="font-style: italic; color: var(--color-ink-tertiary); margin-top: 2rem; border-left: 2px solid var(--color-accent); padding-left: 1.25rem;">It is not an AI operating system. It is an Editorial Intelligence operating system for the AI era.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Hierarchy */
  .hierarchy {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: flex-start;
    max-width: 480px;
  }

  .hierarchy-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: flex-start;
    width: 100%;
  }

  .hierarchy-connector {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    opacity: 0.4;
    padding: 0.2rem 0 0.2rem 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1;
  }

  .hierarchy-item {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 2.5rem 1fr;
    grid-template-rows: auto auto;
    column-gap: 0.75rem;
    padding: 0.875rem 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
    border-radius: 4px;
    text-decoration: none;
    width: 100%;
    transition: background 0.15s;
  }

  .hierarchy-item:hover {
    background: var(--color-surface-secondary);
  }

  .hierarchy-item--current {
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-accent) 40%, var(--color-rule));
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-accent) 5%, transparent);
  }

  .hierarchy-num {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.625rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    grid-row: 1 / 3;
    align-self: center;
    opacity: 0.7;
  }

  .hierarchy-label {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.1rem;
  }

  .hierarchy-sub {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    display: block;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
  }

  /* EE vs EI Cycle distinction */
  .distinction-callout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: var(--color-surface-secondary);
  }

  .distinction-item {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.25rem;
  }

  .distinction-link {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.25rem;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: opacity 0.15s;
  }

  .distinction-link:hover { opacity: 0.8; }

  .distinction-label {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }

  .distinction-role {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.625rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    opacity: 0.7;
  }

  .distinction-desc {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
  }

  .distinction-sep {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-align: center;
    white-space: nowrap;
    writing-mode: vertical-rl;
    opacity: 0.5;
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .distinction-callout {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
    .distinction-sep {
      writing-mode: horizontal-tb;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
      padding-top: 0.75rem;
    }
  }

  .prose-section p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .loop-prose p {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 52ch;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .prose-section p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* Cycle steps */
  .cycle-steps {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }

  .cycle-step {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 2.5rem 1fr;
    gap: 1.5rem;
  }

  .cycle-step__marker {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0;
    padding-top: 0.25rem;
  }

  .cycle-step__line {
    width: 1px;
    flex: 1;
    background: var(--color-surface-tertiary);
    margin: 0.75rem 0;
    min-height: 2rem;
  }

  .cycle-step__content {
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .cycle-step__content p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
  }

  /* Practice examples */
  .practice-example {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-accent-light);
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
  }

  .practice-example p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
  }

  /* Five-stage loop diagram */
  .loop-diagram {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
